Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} and a knob of @?butter{} in a deep #saucepan{}(with a tight-fitting #lid{}) on medium heat. Once hot, add the onion and fry, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

While the onion softens, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{3} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the onion has softened, add the @British smoked bacon lardons{60%grams} to the saucepan. Stir-fry, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook bacon thoroughly.

Add in the garlic. Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%grams} into the onion and lardons until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Pour in the @chicken stock paste{15%grams} and the @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{300%milliliters} for the rice (see pantry for both amounts). Bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, quarter the @baby plum tomatoes{125%grams}.

When the rice is cooked, add the @baby spinach{40%grams} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir through the tomato chunks, @pesto{32%grams} and @sun-dried tomato paste{25%grams} until well combined.

Taste the rice and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if needed.

Divide the pilaf between your #bowls{}.

Drizzle the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%grams} on top and crumble over the @Greek style salad cheese{50%grams} to finish.

Enjoy!